  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Inscription on Standing Alone in Excellence
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven contains the five elements,
    From which the ten thousand things arise.
    Among them, what stands supreme
    Bears the name of man.

    The hills are small and scattered,
    Yet peaks rise solitary and tall;
    Through winter's bitter frost and snow,
    Pine and cypress remain verdant green.

    This is the excellence of things—
    But man alone possesses the highest spirit.
    I wish to stand alone in excellence,
    So I illuminate my virtue and clarity.

    Whence does such achievement come?
    From the sincerity of the heart.
    When the heart leads all beings forth,
    Then peace reigns throughout the realm.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''five elements'' (五行) refer to the fundamental forces in Chinese cosmology: wood, fire, earth, metal, and water.'
    - The imagery of pine and cypress remaining green through harsh winter symbolizes moral constancy and integrity.
    - This work reflects Neo-Confucian ideals, particularly the emphasis on the cultivation of virtue and inner sincerity as the foundation for social harmony.
